All Implemented Interfaces:
ObjectLike
public class JsNotation
extends JsNode

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side Notation nodes.

This class represents a notation declared in the DTD. Programmers working exclusively with HTML documents never need to use this class. A notation either declares, by name, the format of an unparsed entity, or is used for formal declaration of processing instruction targets.

The inherited JsNode.nodeName attribute is set to the declared name of the notation.

The DOM Level 1 does not support editing JsNotation nodes. They are therefore read-only.

A JsNotation node does not have any parent, that is, JsNode.parentNode property for a JsNotation node is always null.

Note that main-stream web browsers do not support the Notation interface declared by the DOM Core Specification. This opaque class inherits directly from JsNode and for documentation purpose only.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.
